    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-01-10T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-01-10T19:00:00-05:00" n="704"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d704">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">882.6351 V. S. Steel Corp./40: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Walton</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-01-10T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >January 10, 1939—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1. The Department is somewhat disturbed to learn that the United States Steel
                    Corporation contemplates recalling its engineers from Liberia for the purpose of
                    consultation before proceeding further with the survey of Liberian iron ore
                    deposits. While we are not yet fully informed as to the reasons for this move,
                    it would seem that the withdrawal of the engineers after only 2 months’
                    activity, unless demonstrated to be technically unavoidable and merely temporary
                    in nature, might lead to criticism that would prove embarrassing to President
                    Barclay.</p>
                <p>Please report by telegraph whatever you may be able to ascertain discreetly
                    regarding this projected step such as the extent of the survey so far made, the
                    results, if any, obtained by the engineers and the necessity for their returning
                    to the United States before completing the survey.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
